# use git

git branches should be used to track work and progress on tasks, with each task being worked on in its own branch. This will help to keep the code organized and make it easier to track changes and progress on specific tasks. When a task is completed, it can be merged back into the main branch with a clear commit message describing the changes that were made.

Branches should be named in a way that clearly indicates the task being worked on, such as "feature/add-pyproject-file" or "bugfix/fix-list-models-output". This will make it easier to understand the purpose of each branch and keep the development process organized.

Once the full task is completed the branch should be merged back into the main branch.

Branches old than 2 weeks should be deleted to keep the repository clean and organized. This will help to avoid confusion and ensure that only active branches are present in the repository.

# update .gitignore

The .gitignore file should be updated to include any files or directories that should not be tracked by git. This could include things like log files, temporary files, or any other files that are generated during the development process but are not necessary to include in the repository.

# minimize the context

In this project I would like you to focus on limiting your thought process by minimizing the context you have to work with. This will help you to focus on the task at hand and avoid getting overwhelmed by too much information. To do this, try to break down the problem into smaller, more manageable pieces and only focus on one piece at a time. This will help you to stay organized and make it easier to find solutions to specific problems without getting lost in the overall complexity of the project.

